# Branching Policy

Always work on a single feature branch at a time in this repository.

## Never start a new branch unless every other branch is already in sync with `main`

Before creating ANY new branch:

1. Check the remote branch list (`git fetch --all --prune && git branch -a`).
2. Confirm that every `cursor/...` branch on the remote has either:
   - Been merged into `main` (its PR is in the `MERGED` state), OR
   - Been deleted from the remote.
3. If ANY unmerged / open `cursor/...` branch still exists (local or remote), do NOT create a new branch.
   Instead, either:
   - Continue committing the new work on that existing open branch, OR
   - Ask the user which branch/PR to merge first, wait for confirmation, and only proceed once `main` is fully up to date with every prior branch's work.

## One-branch rule

- Only one open `cursor/...` branch should exist at any time.
- Do not stack new feature work on top of another unmerged feature branch as a base (e.g. do NOT `git checkout -b cursor/new-thing <another-cursor-branch>`).
- New feature branches are always created directly from an up-to-date local `main`:
  ```
  git checkout main
  git pull origin main
  git checkout -b cursor/<descriptive-name>-<suffix>
  ```

## Clean-up discipline

- When a PR is merged, delete both the local and remote branch before moving on.
- Run `git remote prune origin` after remote branch deletions to drop stale refs.
- If a branch/PR is abandoned, explicitly close the PR and delete the branch instead of leaving it dangling.

## When in doubt

- Prefer continuing work on the currently open feature branch over opening a new one.
- Ask the user to merge the current PR before starting new work if the tasks are independent.
- Keep the working tree, local branches, and remote branches as clean as possible at all times.
